 indigenous peoples while exoticizing and racializing them as inferior Others, Williamson and Hurley sustained colonial fantasies about people of color and the environment as endless resources to be plundered. As Elias demonstrates, their reckless treatment of the sea prefigured attitudes that caused the environmental crises that the oceans and reefs now face.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aCoral reefs and islandsxResearch. 0aEthnologyxSocial aspects. 0aOther (Philosophy) 0aOther (Philosophy). 0aUnderwater explorationxEnvironmental aspects. 0aUnderwater explorationxHistoryy20th century. 0aUnderwater photographyxHistoryy20th century. 0aUnderwater photographyxSocial aspects. 0aVisual anthropology. 7aPhotography / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2019z978311069632540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478004462zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478004462423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781478004462.jpg  a978-3-11-069632-5  DUK eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles